NOVA

Genius Hour
Project

Why I Came Up With My Idea?
So I came up with my idea a while back around the time I was supposed to be working on my first genius hour project, but I was playing minecraft on my school computer. I thought “It would be cool to make a computer in minecraft”. This was before this project was even mentioned so I just played around with it. Then when this was assigned I just transferred my idea.
My purpose for this was mostly just to flex. I wanted to make something cool to impress people, to shock them, to make a showstopper. Also I wanted to demystify computers, I wanted to make something that’s easier to understand than a tiny chip made out of sand and metal powered by controlled lighting going on and off. I wanted to make something more than just ones and zeros.

What Challenges Did I Face?
One of my challenges was I have no knowledge on how any of this works. By knowledge I mean I didn't know the circuitry side of a computer. I knew what a gpu, cpu, ram and a display were but I didn't know the components of these parts but then I didn't know the components of those parts and so on. What I'm saying is I knew what these things are but had zero clue on how they work, how you build it, how you connect and so forth.
Another challenge I faced was I did not know the sheer scale I was working with. I had to take a bunch of logic gates and other components around the size of 1 block to 5 by 5 blocks which is around 1 meter cubed to 5 by 5 meters squared and combine them together into a cpu in our scale the size of a factory. Imagine carrying that to school everyday. Because of that most of my time was spent on building this massive thing.

What Was My Timeline to Create This Project? The Timeline down below is a bit inaccurate due to the fact that most of my time was spent building and researching about my cpu that I went past the deadlines of my Timeline.


How Did I Create My Project? So since I'm making a computer which is a CPU and some memory I had to research and then build each part into Minecraft. So in a typical CPU, we have a control unit (CU, keeps everything running smoothly), arithmetic logic unit (ALU, does math and logic), registers (small storage for 1 word, a 32-bit computer would have 32-bit registers), cache (Small Ram), buses (Data highways), and clock (keeps data flow in rhythm). Some of the things I removed were for the sake of time though. Each of these is made of there own components and each component are made up of logic gates. Also in a typical computer, we have memory like RAM which is volatile memory, once power is out the data’s gone and NVM, non-volatile memory, with and without power doesn’t lose its data. An example of this would be a hard drive. So I built my ram first, then the ALU, then the registers (4 of them), and I topped it off with my CU, Clock, And buses.

What Did I Research?
I researched mostly topics of a specific computer part and then how to build it into Minecraft. Here are the top three links I found the most helpful. Crash Course Computer Sci This crash course on computer science is pretty helpful as it gave me an idea of what to do step-by-step in making this. I found out that there’s a storage inside of your CPU for storing 1 word (words are how many bits the computer can process). Hardware and software - Computer systems - AQA - GCSE Computer Science Revision - AQA - BBC Bitesize This helped me as it gave me a more in-depth look at each of the different components. I found what cache meant, a cache is like RAM but it’s inside of the CPU which means it’s faster and easier to assess. The Cache is mostly used to store data for websites so when you visit them they load faster. Learn Logical Redstone! This linked helped me as it gave me something like a reference book like whenever you want to do something in redstone. I learned that the weird display that you see everwhere is called a 7-segment display.

What Did I Learn From This Project?
I learned a lot form this project. The branch of redstone that includes my computer is called logical redstone. I order to make logical redstone contraptions, you need knowledge in real life computer hardware and logic one of the things I learned with knowledge in redstone mechanics the second thing I learned to make something like my computer. Another thing I learned is how to host a website. I choose github as it’s free and easy to use. All you need to do is set up your url, paste your html - css whatever, wait while up to 10 minutes, and then go to the link and now you have your website. Make sure to set up a index.html page or main page as this the html file that all the html files pigback of. In short, I learned a lot of useful info that will help me in the future.

What Would I Change? I would change only couple things about my computer as the other things like better design I can add on in the future as the basic concept is the same. The number one thing I would chance is the big fat ugly output wire I made. This was completely unessary as you could use one data bus for both i/o save me time. Another thing I would change is instead of having multiple decoders and encoders I could just make two big ones of each simplifying it more. Besides that, theres not a lot to change because it can run programs which are sets of mathematical and logical instructions sort of automatically.

What Would I Like to Make in the Future to Add Onto What I Already Created?
Two things I would like to add out my computer are better memory and a better alu. My current memory systems, my ram and registers are incrediblely inefficient for their size. I would like to make them hold more memory in the same amount of space. My current alu can only do a limited range of operations, addition and subtraction with boolean NOT for negative numbers. I would like to add more operations such as, addition, subtraction, multiplication, and division along with more boolean logic. That is not the only things I would like to add on but these are the most notable.

Picture of My Project

The white wires are output wires leading to the output reg the blue wires are output wires that send info to the input wire which is the green one through another reg. The extions from the top and the midle right are my regsiters and ram and the stuff in the middle is my alu. Then the wires that come out of the bottum are input wires for contraling and data.
